Michael Kovrig and Michael Spavor were clearly arrested in retaliation for the arrest of Meng Wangzhou in Vancouver; their release will not occur without any sort of reciprocation from Canada regarding Meng Wangzhou, and even then remains exceedingly unlikely. Statements from Justin Trudeau indicate the Canadian government will not interfere in the extradition process, which is ongoing and faces repeated delays from Meng Wangzhou's defense team. The situation will not be resolved, and the two Canadians will not be released, before July 15 2021.

Try as they might, Meng Wanzhou's lawyers are attempting to get the judge in the extradition hearing to rule on the admissibility of evidence not normally applicable in extraditions hearings; https://bit.ly/36gZar7 & https://bit.ly/3jSJHWa / https://bit.ly/3hGVWTn.

The process of Meng's extradition trial in Canada could be drawn out beyond 15 May, the originally scheduled end date, as a result of a statement by US Federal Prosecutors that Huawei's lawyers are using embargoed information from the US criminal case in their defence of her extradition trial; https://bloom.bg/3wWQKBo. Either way, it is feasible that China proclaims that US & Canada are colluding in order to ensure Meng's extradition. Although we do not know the extent of the agreement in smells to me though HSBC is either under pressure in HK or attempting appease China. I suspect the former. Will this apparent step forward in Meng's case in Canada be of any use to the two Michaels? That said, Biden's administration may view this as an opportunity to appease Xi / China in some way after the rather terse meeting a few weeks ago. It's very possible IMO that the two Michaels' verdicts in their recent trail may be released around the time of the end of Meng's trial depending on the verdict in Canada. Or, shortly thereafter; https://bit.ly/3a72lEg. This article also highlights that Canada may simply be a bystander in the US v China battle for supremacy.

Meng Wanzhou's extradition hearing in the Canadian Supreme Court gets under way again today (https://bit.ly/30HJhYa). Meng and her lawyers have argued that they should be allowed to admit statements from Huawei employees to substantiate her case that she did not mislead HSBC. However, a Supreme Court Judge has ruled that such evidence it outside the remit of an extradition hearing and the case should proceed (https://bit.ly/3qQI37B). In theory, the current hearing is scheduled for 3 weeks and a decision is expected in May. That would be subject to approval from the relevant Canadian Minister. However, with the potential for appeal by either side, this could drag on past the completion date of this question. This and the recent Chinese 'statement' that Kovrig and Spavor are likely to face trial 'soon' weigh towards little likelihood, in my view, of eithers release within the time frame of this question.

An extremely unfortunate situation. I agree with @thefonz . Until Meng Wanzhou is released and returned, the same will not be done for Michael and Michael. As such I think the real prediction here is 'is there a settlement for the Meng trial prior to 15 July 2021' (with enough time afterward for her to arrive and China and then China to release them). Based on this article https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/10/huawei-cfo-meng-wanzhou-extradition-trial-explained.html there are three phases involved in the trial. One starting January 20th, a second one for June, and a third potential phase in September. The only way these protracted legal proceedings are avoided are that the judge sides with Meng AND there is no appeal, in the January proceedings (focused on double criminality standard) or June proceedings focused on due process during her arrest. The base rate for 'avoiding extradition from Canada to USA' is that 1% of people accomplish this. As such, I am going with a strong 90% probability that the Meng case is not fully sorted out by July 15th. Implicitly I am also assuming that the Biden administration does not choose to drop the charges in his first 5 months as president (to avoid looking 'soft on China'), or finding some other technicality which would result in her release and then the subsequent release of the Michaels. I am not a legal expert though.

There are so many facets to this terrible situation: the connection to Meng Wanzhou and whether she is extradited to the US or returned to China; new US administration that will want to establish a new foreign policy face but will be distracted by domestic issues; China's potential leverage using Kovrig and Spavor to splinter US-Canadian relations. But, since the base rate is the rock upon which estimates should be begin: The Spavor and Kovrig arrests follow a pattern of tit-for-tat arrests in China and Canada. Two Canadians were arrested in China following an arrest in Canada of Chinese nationals (for espionage against the US) in 2014 (https://bit.ly/3q0hRHq). The two Canadians that were arrested in China were sentenced to, and served, two years in prison. Prognosis: poor for Kovrig and Spavor.
